if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_neck_space']=[
  {q:"A 45-year-old diabetic patient presents with fever, neck swelling, trismus, and dysphagia following molar tooth infection. The most likely involved neck space is:",o:["Retropharyngeal space","Submandibular space","Parapharyngeal space","Prevertebral space","Carotid space"],a:1,e:"Odontogenic infections commonly spread into submandibular space causing painful neck swelling and trismus. Airway compromise develops clinically in advanced infections.<br><br>This space is anatomically related to lower molar roots and fascial compartments of floor of mouth.<br><br>Retropharyngeal space (option A), parapharyngeal space (option C), prevertebral space (option D), and carotid space (option E) are less directly related.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Ludwig angina primarily involves the:",o:["Bilateral submandibular and sublingual spaces","Retropharyngeal space","Parotid space","Carotid sheath only","Prevertebral space"],a:0,e:"Ludwig angina is rapidly spreading cellulitis involving bilateral submandibular and sublingual spaces. Tongue elevation and airway compromise develop clinically.<br><br>Dental infections involving lower molars remain the commonest source of infection.<br><br>Parotid space (option C), retropharyngeal space (option B), carotid sheath (option D), and prevertebral space (option E) are less characteristically involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The \"danger space\" of neck extends from skull base to the:",o:["Clavicle","Carina","Superior mediastinum only","Posterior mediastinum and diaphragm","Hyoid bone"],a:3,e:"Danger space lies between alar and prevertebral fascia and extends into posterior mediastinum. Descending mediastinitis develops clinically after deep neck infection spread.<br><br>This anatomical pathway explains life-threatening thoracic complications of cervical sepsis.<br><br>Clavicle (option A), carina (option B), superior mediastinum only (option C), and hyoid bone (option E) are incorrect boundaries.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with retropharyngeal abscess commonly presents with:",o:["Torticollis and dysphagia","Facial paralysis","Epistaxis","Conductive hearing loss","Hemoptysis"],a:0,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess commonly causes painful swallowing and neck stiffness in children. Torticollis develops clinically because of irritation of cervical muscles.<br><br>The retropharyngeal lymph nodes are prominent in childhood and regress later.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option B), epistaxis (option C), hearing loss (option D), and hemoptysis (option E) are less typical features.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina develops stridor and drooling. The immediate management priority is:",o:["Immediate thyroidectomy","Chemotherapy","Airway stabilization","Observation only","Pure tone audiometry"],a:2,e:"Airway compromise is the most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina. Stridor and drooling develop clinically due to floor-of-mouth edema and tongue displacement.<br><br>Securing airway takes priority before antibiotics or surgical drainage procedures.<br><br>Thyroidectomy (option A), chemotherapy (option B), observation (option D), and audiometry (option E) are inappropriate measures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The retropharyngeal space lies between the:",o:["Buccopharyngeal and alar fascia","Pretracheal and investing fascia","Carotid sheath and vertebral fascia","Platysma and investing fascia","Superficial and deep cervical fascia"],a:0,e:"Retropharyngeal space lies between buccopharyngeal fascia anteriorly and alar fascia posteriorly. Dysphagia and posterior pharyngeal wall bulging develop clinically during abscess formation.<br><br>The space extends from skull base to upper mediastinum.<br><br>Pretracheal-investing fascia (option B), carotid sheath relations (option C), platysma-investing fascia (option D), and superficial-deep fascia (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess commonly presents with:",o:["Medial bulging of tonsillar region","Bilateral vocal cord palsy","Nasal obstruction only","Hematemesis","Nystagmus"],a:0,e:"Parapharyngeal abscesses commonly produce medial displacement of tonsil and lateral pharyngeal wall. Fever and trismus develop clinically in severe infections.<br><br>The space communicates closely with deep cervical fascial compartments.<br><br>Bilateral vocal palsy (option B), nasal obstruction (option C), hematemesis (option D), and nystagmus (option E) are less typical findings.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid sheath contains all except:",o:["Internal jugular vein","Common carotid artery","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Internal carotid artery"],a:3,e:"The carotid sheath encloses carotid artery, internal jugular vein, and vagus nerve. Septic thrombophlebitis develops clinically in severe neck infections involving this compartment.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve runs outside the sheath despite close anatomical relation.<br><br>Internal jugular vein (option A), common carotid artery (option B), vagus nerve (option C), and internal carotid artery (option E) are true sheath contents.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with retropharyngeal abscess develops respiratory distress. The preferred investigation is:",o:["CT scan neck with contrast","Pure tone audiometry","Tympanometry","Thyroid scan","Sialography"],a:0,e:"Contrast CT accurately delineates deep neck abscess extent and airway compromise. Fever and dysphagia develop clinically in retropharyngeal infections.<br><br>Imaging helps differentiate cellulitis from drainable abscess collections.<br><br>Audiometry (option B), tympanometry (option C), thyroid scan (option D), and sialography (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Infection from lower molar teeth most commonly spreads to the:",o:["Submandibular space","Parotid space","Retropharyngeal space","Carotid sheath","Prevertebral space"],a:0,e:"Roots of lower molars extend below mylohyoid line, predisposing spread into submandibular space. Painful neck swelling develops clinically after odontogenic infections.<br><br>This anatomical relation explains pathogenesis of Ludwig angina.<br><br>Retropharyngeal space (option C), parotid space (option B), carotid sheath (option D), and prevertebral space (option E) are less commonly involved initially.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess develops severe trismus because of irritation of the:",o:["Masseter and pterygoid muscles","Buccinator muscle","Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Cricothyroid muscle","Platysma"],a:0,e:"Parapharyngeal inflammation commonly irritates muscles of mastication causing marked trismus. Painful mouth opening develops clinically in deep neck infections.<br><br>The masticator space communicates closely with parapharyngeal compartment.<br><br>Buccinator (option B), sternocleidomastoid (option C), cricothyroid (option D), and platysma (option E) contribute less significantly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The retropharyngeal lymph nodes are most prominent in:",o:["Elderly patients","Neonates only","Children","Adults after age 40","Pregnant women"],a:2,e:"Retropharyngeal lymph nodes are well developed during childhood and regress with age. Retropharyngeal abscess develops clinically more commonly in children.<br><br>Upper respiratory infections frequently spread into these nodes in pediatric age groups.<br><br>Elderly patients (option A), neonates only (option B), adults after 40 (option D), and pregnant women (option E) show less prominence.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops septic thrombosis of internal jugular vein. This complication is called:",o:["Horner syndrome","Lemierre syndrome","Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Frey syndrome","Heerfordt syndrome"],a:1,e:"Lemierre syndrome involves septic thrombophlebitis of internal jugular vein after oropharyngeal infection. Fever and septic emboli develop clinically in severe disease.<br><br>Fusobacterium necrophorum remains a classic causative organism.<br><br>Horner syndrome (option A), Ramsay Hunt syndrome (option C), Frey syndrome (option D), and Heerfordt syndrome (option E) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess shows bulging posterior pharyngeal wall. The abscess is best drained through:",o:["Transoral approach in selected cases","Radical neck dissection","Total thyroidectomy","Mastoidectomy","Endoscopic sinus surgery"],a:0,e:"Selected retropharyngeal abscesses may be drained transorally under controlled airway conditions. Dysphagia and muffled voice develop clinically with posterior pharyngeal swelling.<br><br>Lateral or extensive abscesses may require external cervical drainage.<br><br>Neck dissection (option B), thyroidectomy (option C), mastoidectomy (option D), and sinus surgery (option E) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The prevertebral space lies between:",o:["Alar fascia and prevertebral fascia","Buccopharyngeal and alar fascia","Investing and pretracheal fascia","Platysma and investing fascia","Carotid sheath and trachea"],a:0,e:"The prevertebral space lies posterior to danger space and surrounds vertebral musculature. Neck pain and restricted movement develop clinically in infections involving this compartment.<br><br>Extension may occur into posterior mediastinum in severe disease.<br><br>Buccopharyngeal-alar plane (option B), investing-pretracheal plane (option C), platysma-investing fascia (option D), and carotid-tracheal plane (option E) are different spaces.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with Ludwig angina receives intravenous antibiotics. Which additional measure is commonly required when fluctuation develops?",o:["Observation only","Surgical drainage","Cochlear implantation","Thyroid suppression therapy","Radiotherapy"],a:1,e:"Abscess formation within deep neck spaces often requires surgical drainage despite antibiotic therapy. Persistent fever and airway edema develop clinically in progressive infections.<br><br>Drainage reduces bacterial load and prevents descending mediastinitis.<br><br>Observation (option A), cochlear implantation (option C), thyroid suppression (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The fascial layer enclosing sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles is the:",o:["Investing layer of deep cervical fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Alar fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Pretracheal fascia"],a:0,e:"The investing layer surrounds sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles and forms major cervical fascial compartment. Neck abscess spread develops clinically along fascial planes.<br><br>This fascia contributes to boundaries of several cervical spaces.<br><br>Alar fascia (option C), buccopharyngeal fascia (option B), prevertebral fascia (option D), and pretracheal fascia (option E) are different layers.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess develops cranial nerve palsies. The likely explanation is spread to the:",o:["Carotid space","Masticator space only","Submental space","Prelaryngeal space","Buccal space"],a:0,e:"Parapharyngeal infections may extend into carotid space affecting lower cranial nerves. Dysphagia and vocal cord paralysis develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>The carotid sheath contains major neurovascular structures vulnerable to compression or inflammation.<br><br>Masticator space (option B), submental space (option C), prelaryngeal space (option D), and buccal space (option E) are less associated with cranial neuropathies.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck space infection develops chest pain and sepsis. The most feared complication is:",o:["Descending mediastinitis","Otitis externa","Bell palsy","Mastoiditis","Ménière disease"],a:0,e:"Deep cervical infections may spread inferiorly through danger space into mediastinum. Severe sepsis and chest pain develop clinically in descending mediastinitis.<br><br>Mortality remains high without aggressive drainage and intensive care.<br><br>Otitis externa (option B), Bell palsy (option C), mastoiditis (option D), and Ménière disease (option E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina commonly demonstrates:",o:["Tongue elevation and woody induration","Facial twitching","Hemotympanum","Nasal septal perforation","Exophthalmos"],a:0,e:"Ludwig angina produces firm \"woody\" cellulitis of submandibular region with tongue displacement. Dysphagia and airway compromise develop clinically rapidly.<br><br>Bilateral sublingual edema contributes to elevation of tongue base.<br><br>Facial twitching (option B), hemotympanum (option C), septal perforation (option D), and exophthalmos (option E) are unrelated signs.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess prefers sitting position with neck extended because:",o:["It improves venous drainage","It reduces airway obstruction","It improves hearing","It prevents salivation","It relieves facial pain only"],a:1,e:"Patients with retropharyngeal abscess often adopt extension posture to maintain airway patency. Stridor and dysphagia develop clinically with progressive posterior pharyngeal swelling.<br><br>Supine positioning may worsen upper airway compromise significantly.<br><br>Venous drainage (option A), hearing improvement (option C), salivation prevention (option D), and facial pain relief (option E) are less important.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The submental space is located between:",o:["Mylohyoid muscle and platysma","Buccopharyngeal fascia and alar fascia","Carotid sheath and vertebral fascia","Thyroid cartilage and trachea","Sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles"],a:0,e:"The submental space lies between mylohyoid muscle floor and superficial cervical tissues. Midline floor-of-mouth infections develop clinically within this compartment.<br><br>It communicates laterally with submandibular spaces.<br><br>Buccopharyngeal-alar plane (option B), carotid-vertebral plane (option C), thyroid-tracheal relation (option D), and sternocleidomastoid-trapezius relation (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with odontogenic infection develops inability to open mouth fully. The symptom is termed:",o:["Aphonia","Dysarthria","Trismus","Stridor","Dysphonia"],a:2,e:"Trismus results from inflammation involving muscles of mastication during deep neck infections. Painful restricted mouth opening develops clinically in parapharyngeal or masticator space disease.<br><br>Severe trismus complicates airway management and oral examination.<br><br>Aphonia (option A), dysarthria (option B), stridor (option D), and dysphonia (option E) are different clinical symptoms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The space most commonly involved in spread of tonsillar infections is the:",o:["Parapharyngeal space","Submental space","Retropharyngeal space","Prevertebral space","Parotid space"],a:0,e:"Tonsillar infections commonly spread laterally into parapharyngeal space. Fever, trismus, and medial tonsillar bulging develop clinically.<br><br>Close anatomical relation between tonsillar bed and lateral pharyngeal compartment explains this spread.<br><br>Submental space (option B), retropharyngeal space (option C), prevertebral space (option D), and parotid space (option E) are less directly involved.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina may require tracheostomy because of:",o:["Bilateral vocal nodules","Septal hematoma","Chronic otitis media","Tongue base airway obstruction","Salivary fistula"],a:3,e:"Massive edema of sublingual and submandibular spaces elevates tongue posteriorly. Stridor and respiratory distress develop clinically in advanced Ludwig angina.<br><br>Emergency tracheostomy may become necessary when intubation is difficult or unsafe.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option A), chronic otitis media (option C), septal hematoma (option B), and salivary fistula (option E) are unrelated causes.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The danger space is termed so because infections can spread rapidly to the:",o:["Orbit","Thyroid gland","Cranial cavity only","Mediastinum","Salivary glands"],a:3,e:"Danger space provides direct fascial pathway from skull base to posterior mediastinum. Severe sepsis develops clinically when infection descends into thoracic cavity.<br><br>This complication carries high mortality despite modern treatment.<br><br>Orbit (option A), cranial cavity only (option C), thyroid gland (option B), and salivary glands (option E) are less characteristic spread sites.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with retropharyngeal abscess develops aspiration during examination. The likely mechanism is:",o:["Facial nerve paralysis","Septal deviation","Vocal cord papilloma","Spontaneous abscess rupture","Salivary gland obstruction"],a:3,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess may rupture spontaneously into airway causing aspiration and sudden respiratory compromise. Severe coughing develops clinically during rupture episodes.<br><br>Careful airway precautions are therefore essential during examination and drainage.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), vocal papilloma (option C), septal deviation (option B), and salivary obstruction (option E) are unrelated causes.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The fascial layer surrounding thyroid gland, trachea, and esophagus is the:",o:["Pretracheal fascia","Alar fascia","Investing fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Prevertebral fascia"],a:0,e:"Pretracheal fascia encloses thyroid gland, trachea, and esophagus within visceral compartment of neck. Infection spread develops clinically along this fascial plane.<br><br>It extends inferiorly into superior mediastinum.<br><br>Investing fascia (option C), alar fascia (option B), buccopharyngeal fascia (option D), and prevertebral fascia (option E) surround different structures.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess develops Horner syndrome. The involved structure is the:",o:["Facial nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:1,e:"Parapharyngeal infections may involve cervical sympathetic chain causing Horner syndrome. Ptosis and miosis develop clinically after sympathetic disruption.<br><br>The sympathetic chain lies close to carotid sheath structures within deep neck spaces.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option C), phrenic nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest source of deep neck space infections in adults is:",o:["Chronic otitis media","Thyroid nodules","Viral rhinitis","Dental infections","Salivary tumors"],a:3,e:"Odontogenic infections remain the leading cause of deep neck space infections in adults. Painful neck swelling and dysphagia develop clinically after spread through fascial planes.<br><br>Lower molar infections particularly predispose to submandibular space involvement.<br><br>Chronic otitis media (option A), viral rhinitis (option C), thyroid nodules (option B), and salivary tumors (option E) are less common causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 52-year-old diabetic man presents to the emergency department with rapidly progressive bilateral submandibular swelling after lower molar toothache. He has fever, muffled \"hot potato\" voice, drooling, tongue elevation, and increasing respiratory distress. Examination reveals woody induration of floor of mouth without obvious fluctuance. Oxygen saturation is falling despite supplemental oxygen. The most important immediate management step is:",o:["Immediate incision and drainage under local anesthesia","Broad-spectrum oral antibiotics only","Airway stabilization with definitive airway control","Needle aspiration of submental space","Emergency tonsillectomy"],a:2,e:"This patient has Ludwig angina with impending airway obstruction from bilateral submandibular and sublingual cellulitis. Stridor and tongue elevation develop clinically because edema displaces tongue posteriorly.<br><br>Airway management takes absolute priority before imaging or drainage procedures because sudden airway collapse may occur rapidly.<br><br>Incision and drainage alone (option A), oral antibiotics (option B), aspiration (option D), and tonsillectomy (option E) are insufficient initial measures.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 6-year-old child presents with fever, severe odynophagia, neck stiffness, drooling, and refusal to extend the neck. Examination shows bulging of posterior pharyngeal wall and inspiratory stridor. Contrast CT demonstrates large retropharyngeal abscess with airway narrowing. The preferred definitive management is:",o:["Oral antihistamines only","Observation with hydration","Intravenous antibiotics with surgical drainage","Radical neck dissection","Thyroidectomy"],a:2,e:"Large retropharyngeal abscesses with airway compromise require urgent drainage in addition to intravenous antibiotics. Dysphagia and torticollis develop clinically because of retropharyngeal inflammation.<br><br>Delay in treatment increases risk of aspiration, airway obstruction, and mediastinal spread.<br><br>Antihistamines (option A), observation (option B), neck dissection (option D), and thyroidectomy (option E) are inappropriate treatments.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 38-year-old man presents with severe sore throat, high-grade fever, trismus, medial bulging of right tonsillar pillar, and painful neck swelling after untreated tonsillitis. CT scan reveals parapharyngeal abscess extending toward carotid sheath. Which complication is most feared in this patient?",o:["Septal hematoma","Facial nerve paralysis","Internal jugular vein thrombosis","Cholesteatoma formation","Conductive hearing loss"],a:2,e:"Parapharyngeal infections may spread into carotid sheath causing septic thrombophlebitis of internal jugular vein. Septic emboli and systemic sepsis develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>This potentially fatal complication forms part of Lemierre syndrome.<br><br>Septal hematoma (option A), facial paralysis (option B), cholesteatoma (option D), and conductive hearing loss (option E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old patient with neglected odontogenic infection develops chest pain, tachycardia, severe sepsis, and dyspnea several days after treatment for deep neck abscess. CT chest reveals mediastinal fluid collections. The anatomical pathway responsible for spread of infection is the:",o:["Pretracheal fascia only","Investing fascia","Danger space","Carotid sheath exclusively","Buccal space"],a:2,e:"The danger space extends from skull base to posterior mediastinum and permits rapid descending infection spread. Severe sepsis and respiratory compromise develop clinically in descending mediastinitis.<br><br>Mortality remains extremely high without aggressive surgical drainage and intensive care support.<br><br>Pretracheal fascia (option A), investing fascia (option B), carotid sheath (option D), and buccal space (option E) are less direct routes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old diabetic woman with Ludwig angina undergoes emergency surgical drainage. Postoperatively she develops persistent inability to protrude tongue toward the opposite side. Which nerve was most likely injured during deep cervical dissection?",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:2,e:"The hypoglossal nerve courses close to submandibular region and may be injured during extensive drainage procedures. Tongue deviation develops clinically toward side of lesion because of ipsilateral paralysis.<br><br>Careful dissection within floor-of-mouth and upper neck compartments minimizes this complication.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option B), accessory nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) cause different deficits.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 10-year-old child with retropharyngeal abscess suddenly develops severe coughing, cyanosis, and respiratory collapse while being examined in supine position. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Acute epiglottitis","Laryngeal papillomatosis","Bilateral vocal cord paralysis","Spontaneous rupture and aspiration of abscess","Pulmonary embolism"],a:3,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess may rupture spontaneously into airway during examination or anesthesia. Sudden aspiration develops clinically with respiratory distress and cyanosis.<br><br>Careful airway precautions and upright positioning are therefore important before drainage procedures.<br><br>Epiglottitis (option A), vocal cord paralysis (option C), papillomatosis (option B), and pulmonary embolism (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection presents with ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis on the affected side along with painful neck swelling and dysphagia. The syndrome results from involvement of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Vagus nerve","Lingual nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Accessory nerve"],a:3,e:"Deep neck infections extending into carotid or parapharyngeal space may involve cervical sympathetic chain. Horner syndrome develops clinically with ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis.<br><br>This indicates extensive deep space disease close to carotid sheath structures.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and accessory nerve (option E) produce different neurological findings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 47-year-old alcoholic patient presents with fever, severe trismus, unilateral neck swelling, and medial displacement of tonsil. Contrast CT demonstrates parapharyngeal abscess with gas formation. Which organism classically associated with septic internal jugular thrombosis should be suspected?",o:["Candida albicans","Staphylococcus epidermidis","Fusobacterium necrophorum","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Corynebacterium diphtheriae"],a:2,e:"Fusobacterium necrophorum is classically associated with severe anaerobic deep neck infections and Lemierre syndrome. Septic embolization develops clinically following internal jugular vein thrombosis.<br><br>Prompt intravenous antibiotics and drainage are critical to reduce mortality.<br><br>Candida (option A), Staphylococcus epidermidis (option B), tuberculosis (option D), and diphtheria (option E) are less typical organisms.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old patient with odontogenic infection develops rapidly progressive submandibular swelling and marked trismus. Examination reveals inability to palpate fluctuation despite severe cellulitis. This \"woody\" induration is characteristic of:",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Ludwig angina","Parotid abscess","Branchial cyst infection","Thyroglossal fistula infection"],a:1,e:"Ludwig angina classically produces diffuse brawny cellulitis with hard \"woody\" induration rather than localized fluctuance. Dysphagia and tongue elevation develop clinically early in disease.<br><br>The infection spreads rapidly through fascial planes of submandibular compartments bilaterally.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (option A), parotid abscess (option C), branchial cyst infection (option D), and thyroglossal infection (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with extensive parapharyngeal abscess undergoes surgical drainage. Several days later he develops persistent shoulder drooping and inability to abduct shoulder above horizontal. Which structure was most likely injured during posterior triangle extension of surgery?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Accessory nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:2,e:"The spinal accessory nerve traverses posterior triangle superficially and remains vulnerable during extensive cervical surgery. Trapezius weakness develops clinically causing shoulder droop and impaired abduction.<br><br>Preservation of this nerve is essential during drainage of deep lateral neck infections.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option B), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old diabetic patient presents with rapidly progressive submandibular swelling, fever, drooling, muffled voice, and tongue elevation after lower molar infection. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Parotid abscess","Branchial cyst infection","Ludwig angina","Thyroglossal abscess"],a:3,e:"Ludwig angina is rapidly spreading cellulitis involving bilateral submandibular and sublingual spaces. Airway compromise develops clinically because edema elevates tongue posteriorly.<br><br>Dental infections involving lower molars remain the commonest source.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (option A), branchial cyst infection (option C), parotid abscess (option B), and thyroglossal abscess (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous immediate complication of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Thyroid storm","Conductive hearing loss","Airway obstruction","Bell palsy"],a:3,e:"Massive floor-of-mouth edema displaces tongue posteriorly causing airway narrowing. Stridor and respiratory distress develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Airway management therefore takes absolute priority before definitive drainage procedures.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), hearing loss (option C), thyroid storm (option B), and Bell palsy (option E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with fever, torticollis, drooling, and posterior pharyngeal wall bulging most likely has:",o:["Parotid abscess","Peritonsillar abscess","Thyroglossal cyst","Retropharyngeal abscess","Masticator space infection"],a:3,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess commonly affects children because retropharyngeal lymph nodes are prominent in early life. Neck stiffness and dysphagia develop clinically.<br><br>Bulging posterior pharyngeal wall is an important examination finding.<br><br>Parotid abscess (option A), peritonsillar abscess (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option C), and masticator infection (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for evaluating deep neck space abscess is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","CT scan with contrast","Tympanometry","Thyroid scan","Sialography"],a:1,e:"Contrast-enhanced CT accurately delineates extent of infection and differentiates cellulitis from abscess formation. Fever and trismus develop clinically in advanced infections.<br><br>Imaging also helps guide surgical drainage planning.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), tympanometry (option C), thyroid scan (option D), and sialography (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess commonly develops trismus because of involvement of the:",o:["Platysma muscle","Cricothyroid muscle","Muscles of mastication","Sternohyoid muscle","Buccinator muscle only"],a:2,e:"Parapharyngeal inflammation irritates medial pterygoid and surrounding masticatory muscles. Painful restricted mouth opening develops clinically in deep neck infections.<br><br>Severe trismus may complicate airway access and oral examination.<br><br>Platysma (option A), cricothyroid (option B), sternohyoid (option D), and buccinator alone (option E) are less important causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops septic thrombosis of internal jugular vein. The condition is termed:",o:["Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Frey syndrome","Horner syndrome","Lemierre syndrome","Eagle syndrome"],a:3,e:"Lemierre syndrome refers to septic thrombophlebitis of internal jugular vein after oropharyngeal infection. Septic pulmonary emboli develop clinically in severe disease.<br><br>Fusobacterium necrophorum is classically implicated.<br><br>Ramsay Hunt syndrome (option A), Frey syndrome (option B), Horner syndrome (option C), and Eagle syndrome (option E) are unrelated disorders.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina requires emergency tracheostomy because:",o:["Vocal cord papilloma is present","Tympanic membrane perforates","Nasal obstruction occurs","Tongue base airway obstruction develops","Facial edema alone develops"],a:3,e:"Edema within sublingual spaces elevates tongue backward causing upper airway compromise. Stridor and drooling develop clinically in advanced Ludwig angina.<br><br>Tracheostomy may become lifesaving when oral intubation is difficult.<br><br>Vocal papilloma (option A), nasal obstruction (option C), tympanic perforation (option B), and facial edema alone (option E) are unrelated causes.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess suddenly develops severe coughing and cyanosis during examination. The most likely event is:",o:["Laryngeal edema only","Septic embolism","Spontaneous rupture with aspiration","Facial nerve paralysis","Acute asthma attack"],a:2,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess may rupture spontaneously into airway causing aspiration and respiratory collapse. Sudden coughing develops clinically during rupture.<br><br>Careful airway precautions are essential during examination and drainage procedures.<br><br>Laryngeal edema (option A), septic embolism (option B), facial paralysis (option D), and asthma (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest source of deep neck space infections in adults is:",o:["Viral rhinitis","Chronic otitis media","Thyroid nodules","Dental infections","Salivary tumors"],a:3,e:"Odontogenic infections remain the leading cause of deep neck infections in adults. Painful neck swelling and dysphagia develop clinically after spread along fascial planes.<br><br>Lower molars particularly predispose to submandibular involvement.<br><br>Viral rhinitis (option A), chronic otitis media (option B), thyroid nodules (option C), and salivary tumors (option E) are less common causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess demonstrates medial displacement of the tonsil because the abscess lies:",o:["Posterior to vertebral fascia","Beneath platysma only","Within thyroid gland","Lateral to pharyngeal wall","Inside carotid artery sheath exclusively"],a:3,e:"Parapharyngeal abscesses occupy lateral pharyngeal compartment causing medial tonsillar displacement. Dysphagia and muffled voice develop clinically commonly.<br><br>This characteristic finding assists diagnosis during oropharyngeal examination.<br><br>Posterior vertebral fascia (option A), thyroid gland (option C), platysma plane (option B), and carotid sheath exclusively (option E) are incorrect sites.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with extensive neck infection develops chest pain and severe sepsis. The most feared complication is:",o:["Mastoiditis","Ménière disease","Bell palsy","Descending mediastinitis","Otitis externa"],a:3,e:"Deep cervical infections may descend into mediastinum through fascial planes. Severe sepsis and respiratory distress develop clinically in descending mediastinitis.<br><br>Mortality remains high without aggressive surgical drainage and ICU care.<br><br>Mastoiditis (option A), Bell palsy (option C), Ménière disease (option B), and otitis externa (option E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient with Ludwig angina receives intravenous antibiotics but remains febrile with fluctuant neck swelling. The next step is:",o:["Observation only","Surgical drainage","Thyroidectomy","Mastoidectomy","Radiotherapy"],a:1,e:"Deep neck abscesses require drainage when fluctuation persists despite antibiotics. Persistent fever and toxic appearance develop clinically in abscess formation.<br><br>Drainage reduces bacterial load and prevents mediastinal spread.<br><br>Observation (option A), thyroidectomy (option C), mastoidectomy (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis. The involved structure is the:",o:["Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:2,e:"Involvement of cervical sympathetic chain causes Horner syndrome in deep neck infections. Ptosis and miosis develop clinically because sympathetic fibers are disrupted.<br><br>This usually indicates extensive carotid or parapharyngeal space disease.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) cause different deficits.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe trismus, fever, and cheek swelling after dental infection most likely has infection involving the:",o:["Masticator space","Retropharyngeal space","Prevertebral space","Carotid sheath","Prelaryngeal space"],a:0,e:"Masticator space infections classically produce severe trismus because muscles of mastication become inflamed. Facial swelling develops clinically with painful jaw movement.<br><br>Odontogenic infections commonly spread into this compartment.<br><br>Retropharyngeal space (option B), prevertebral space (option C), carotid sheath (option D), and prelaryngeal space (option E) show different presentations.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with retropharyngeal abscess prefers sitting with neck extended because this position:",o:["Improves hearing","Relieves facial pain","Prevents salivation","Reduces airway obstruction","Decreases trismus only"],a:3,e:"Patients with retropharyngeal abscess often adopt neck extension to maintain airway patency. Dysphagia and stridor develop clinically because posterior pharyngeal swelling narrows airway.<br><br>Supine positioning may worsen respiratory compromise significantly.<br><br>Hearing improvement (option A), facial pain relief (option B), salivation prevention (option C), and isolated trismus reduction (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina develops inability to protrude tongue properly after surgical drainage. The injured nerve is most likely:",o:["Facial nerve","Accessory nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:2,e:"The hypoglossal nerve runs close to submandibular region and may be injured during deep cervical drainage. Tongue deviation develops clinically toward side of injury.<br><br>Careful dissection is essential during surgical management of floor-of-mouth infections.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), accessory nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and vagus nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The danger space is clinically important because it allows infection spread from neck to the:",o:["Orbit","Thyroid gland","Salivary glands","Mediastinum","External auditory canal"],a:3,e:"Danger space extends from skull base to diaphragm permitting rapid spread of cervical infections. Severe sepsis develops clinically in descending mediastinitis.<br><br>Recognition of this pathway is important in aggressive management of deep neck infections.<br><br>Orbit (option A), thyroid gland (option B), salivary glands (option C), and auditory canal (option E) are less relevant spread sites.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal abscess develops hoarseness and dysphagia. Which structure is likely involved?",o:["Facial nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:3,e:"The vagus nerve traverses carotid sheath and may be compressed in parapharyngeal infections. Hoarseness develops clinically because recurrent laryngeal fibers become affected.<br><br>Associated dysphagia suggests lower cranial nerve involvement.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), accessory nerve (option B), and phrenic nerve (option E) cause different symptoms.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck abscess is noted to have \"hot potato\" voice. This sign usually indicates:",o:["Vocal cord carcinoma","Middle ear effusion","Facial nerve injury","Oropharyngeal and parapharyngeal swelling","Thyroid storm"],a:3,e:"A muffled \"hot potato\" voice results from pharyngeal edema and reduced oral resonance. Dysphagia and drooling develop clinically in severe infections.<br><br>It commonly occurs in peritonsillar and parapharyngeal abscesses.<br><br>Vocal cord carcinoma (option A), facial nerve injury (option C), middle ear effusion (option B), and thyroid storm (option E) are less likely causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with odontogenic deep neck infection develops persistent shoulder droop after surgery involving posterior triangle. The injured nerve is:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve","Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:1,e:"The spinal accessory nerve traverses posterior triangle superficially and remains vulnerable during extensive drainage procedures. Trapezius paralysis develops clinically causing shoulder droop.<br><br>Preservation of this nerve is important during neck surgery.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), facial nerve (option D), and glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess is at highest risk of aspiration during:",o:["Sitting position","Nasal examination only","Walking","Oral examination and anesthesia induction","Otoscopy"],a:3,e:"Manipulation of retropharyngeal abscess may precipitate rupture into airway causing aspiration. Sudden coughing and cyanosis develop clinically after rupture.<br><br>Controlled airway precautions are therefore mandatory before intervention.<br><br>Sitting position (option A), walking (option C), nasal examination (option B), and otoscopy (option E) are less risky situations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe neck infection develops septic pulmonary emboli. The most likely primary complication is:",o:["Carotid artery rupture","Mastoiditis","Facial cellulitis","Internal jugular vein thrombophlebitis","Thyroid abscess"],a:3,e:"Septic thrombophlebitis of internal jugular vein may shower septic emboli into lungs. Fever and respiratory symptoms develop clinically in Lemierre syndrome.<br><br>This complication usually follows severe oropharyngeal infection.<br><br>Carotid rupture (option A), facial cellulitis (option C), mastoiditis (option B), and thyroid abscess (option E) are less likely causes.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina has \"woody\" induration rather than fluctuance because the condition is primarily:",o:["Necrotizing vasculitis","Cellulitis of fascial planes","Tuberculous granuloma","Viral edema only","Neoplastic infiltration"],a:1,e:"Ludwig angina is primarily diffuse cellulitis involving fascial compartments rather than localized abscess formation initially. Hard brawny swelling develops clinically.<br><br>Fluctuation may appear later if abscesses develop secondarily.<br><br>Necrotizing vasculitis (option A), tuberculosis (option C), viral edema (option D), and neoplastic infiltration (option E) are incorrect mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection undergoes CT scan showing gas-forming infection within fascial planes. This finding most strongly suggests:",o:["Viral infection","Allergic edema","Fungal rhinitis","Anaerobic bacterial infection","Autoimmune disease"],a:3,e:"Gas formation within deep tissues strongly suggests anaerobic bacterial involvement. Severe toxicity and tissue destruction develop clinically in aggressive infections.<br><br>Mixed odontogenic flora commonly produce gas within cervical fascial compartments.<br><br>Viral infection (option A), fungal rhinitis (option C), allergic edema (option B), and autoimmune disease (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The best indicator that a deep neck infection has become surgically drainable is:",o:["Fever alone","Nasal obstruction","Mild odynophagia only","Fluctuation or radiological abscess collection","Ear fullness"],a:3,e:"Deep neck abscesses require drainage once pus collection is established clinically or radiologically. Persistent fever and toxic appearance develop clinically in abscess formation.<br><br>CT imaging helps differentiate cellulitis from drainable abscesses accurately.<br><br>Fever alone (option A), mild odynophagia (option C), nasal obstruction (option B), and ear fullness (option E) are insufficient indicators.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with extensive parapharyngeal infection develops brisk hemorrhage during drainage. The most likely injured structure is the:",o:["External carotid artery","Facial vein","Lingual nerve","Thyroid gland","Internal auditory artery"],a:0,e:"Major vessels lie close to parapharyngeal space and may be endangered during deep abscess drainage. Massive hemorrhage develops clinically after vascular injury.<br><br>Careful preoperative imaging and surgical planning are therefore essential.<br><br>Facial vein (option B), lingual nerve (option C), thyroid gland (option D), and internal auditory artery (option E) are less likely sources.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with untreated odontogenic infection develops severe bilateral floor-of-mouth swelling but minimal localized pus collection. The diagnosis is:",o:["Parotid abscess","Thyroglossal abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Branchial fistula infection","Ludwig angina"],a:4,e:"Ludwig angina is characterized by diffuse cellulitis involving bilateral submandibular spaces with minimal early abscess formation. Airway compromise develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Lower molar infections remain the commonest precipitating factor.<br><br>Parotid abscess (option A), retropharyngeal abscess (option C), branchial infection (option D), and thyroglossal abscess (option B) present differently.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess develops neck extension rigidity because inflammation irritates:",o:["Facial muscles","Prevertebral muscles","Orbicularis oris","Platysma only","Cricothyroid muscle"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal inflammation irritates prevertebral musculature causing painful neck stiffness and torticollis. Dysphagia develops clinically because of posterior pharyngeal swelling.<br><br>This sign is particularly common in pediatric retropharyngeal infections.<br><br>Facial muscles (option A), orbicularis oris (option C), platysma (option D), and cricothyroid muscle (option E) are less involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe deep neck infection is found to have uncontrolled diabetes mellitus. The presence of diabetes mainly worsens prognosis because it:",o:["Causes hearing loss","Leads to otosclerosis","Produces septal deviation","Causes vocal nodules","Reduces host immune response"],a:4,e:"Diabetes predisposes to severe rapidly spreading infections because neutrophil function and tissue perfusion become impaired. Necrotizing infections develop clinically more aggressively.<br><br>Strict glycemic control is therefore important during management.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A), septal deviation (option C), vocal nodules (option D), and otosclerosis (option B) are unrelated effects.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina improves after airway stabilization, antibiotics, and drainage. Which preventive measure most effectively reduces future recurrence risk?",o:["Tonsillectomy","Thyroid suppression therapy","Septoplasty","Tympanoplasty","Extraction or treatment of infected teeth"],a:4,e:"Odontogenic infections are the leading cause of Ludwig angina. Recurrent cervical infections develop clinically if dental source remains untreated.<br><br>Definitive dental treatment is therefore essential after acute stabilization.<br><br>Tonsillectomy (option A), septoplasty (option C), tympanoplasty (option D), and thyroid suppression (option B) do not address the primary cause.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old diabetic man presents with rapidly progressive neck swelling after extraction of an infected mandibular molar. He has fever, drooling, muffled voice, trismus, and severe pain radiating to the chest. CT scan demonstrates extensive gas-forming infection involving submandibular, parapharyngeal, and retropharyngeal spaces with mediastinal extension. Despite antibiotics, he remains hypotensive and tachycardic. The most appropriate next step is:",o:["Oral antibiotics and discharge","Emergency tracheostomy with aggressive surgical drainage","Observation in ward only","Immediate thyroidectomy","Radiotherapy"],a:1,e:"This patient has severe necrotizing deep neck infection with descending mediastinitis and impending airway compromise. Septic shock develops clinically in advanced polymicrobial cervical infections.<br><br>Aggressive airway control, drainage of all involved spaces, and intensive care support are lifesaving.<br><br>Oral antibiotics (option A), observation (option C), thyroidectomy (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with retropharyngeal abscess develops sudden neck swelling, hoarseness, and brisk bleeding into the pharynx during attempted drainage. The most likely catastrophic complication is:",o:["Internal carotid artery erosion","Facial nerve paralysis","Septal hematoma","Otitis externa","Vocal nodules"],a:0,e:"Deep retropharyngeal infections may erode major cervical vessels causing life-threatening hemorrhage. Sudden airway compromise develops clinically with active bleeding into pharynx.<br><br>Prompt vascular control and airway stabilization become critical emergency measures.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option B), septal hematoma (option C), otitis externa (option D), and vocal nodules (option E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old patient with severe sore throat, trismus, and neck swelling develops septic pulmonary emboli and respiratory distress. Blood cultures grow Fusobacterium necrophorum. The underlying complication is:",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Lemierre syndrome","Bezold abscess","Gradenigo syndrome","Frey syndrome"],a:1,e:"Lemierre syndrome consists of septic thrombophlebitis of internal jugular vein following oropharyngeal infection. Septic embolization to lungs develops clinically causing respiratory compromise.<br><br>Fusobacterium necrophorum remains the classical organism implicated in this syndrome.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (option A), Bezold abscess (option C), Gradenigo syndrome (option D), and Frey syndrome (option E) are unrelated entities.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina develops severe tongue elevation and inability to tolerate supine position. Which clinical sign most strongly suggests impending airway obstruction?",o:["Mild odynophagia","Halitosis","Stridor at rest","Tender cervical nodes","Gingival edema only"],a:2,e:"Stridor at rest indicates critical airway narrowing and impending respiratory collapse in Ludwig angina. Posterior displacement of tongue develops clinically because of extensive sublingual edema.<br><br>Immediate airway protection is mandatory before further investigations or drainage.<br><br>Mild odynophagia (option A), halitosis (option B), cervical nodes (option D), and gingival edema (option E) are less urgent findings.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old patient with parapharyngeal abscess develops ptosis, miosis, hoarseness, and dysphagia. These findings suggest extension into the:",o:["Buccal space only","Masticator space alone","Submental space","Prelaryngeal space","Carotid sheath compartment"],a:4,e:"Extension of infection into carotid sheath may involve vagus nerve and cervical sympathetic chain. Horner syndrome and vocal cord paralysis develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>This finding indicates severe deep neck infection with high complication risk.<br><br>Buccal space (option A), submental space (option C), prelaryngeal space (option D), and isolated masticator space (option B) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess undergoes induction of general anesthesia and suddenly develops complete airway collapse. The most likely mechanism is:",o:["Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy","Tracheomalacia","Acute bronchial asthma","Pulmonary edema","Aspiration after abscess rupture"],a:4,e:"Manipulation and muscle relaxation during anesthesia may precipitate spontaneous abscess rupture into airway. Sudden aspiration develops clinically with cyanosis and respiratory collapse.<br><br>Controlled airway strategies are therefore essential before anesthesia induction.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal palsy (option A), asthma (option C), pulmonary edema (option D), and tracheomalacia (option B) are less likely causes.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with uncontrolled diabetic ketoacidosis develops rapidly spreading cervical cellulitis with crepitus and skin discoloration. CT scan demonstrates widespread fascial necrosis and gas formation. The diagnosis is:",o:["Tuberculous lymphadenitis","Necrotizing fasciitis of neck","Branchial fistula infection","Thyroglossal abscess","Viral lymphadenitis"],a:1,e:"Necrotizing fasciitis is a fulminant polymicrobial infection causing tissue necrosis and gas formation. Septic shock develops clinically with rapidly progressive skin discoloration and crepitus.<br><br>Urgent radical debridement and broad-spectrum antibiotics are mandatory.<br><br>Tuberculous lymphadenitis (option A), branchial infection (option C), thyroglossal abscess (option D), and viral lymphadenitis (option E) progress less aggressively.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops shoulder droop and inability to abduct arm above shoulder level following drainage of posterior triangle abscess. Which nerve was injured?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Marginal mandibular nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:4,e:"The spinal accessory nerve traverses posterior triangle superficially and remains vulnerable during extensive drainage procedures. Trapezius paralysis develops clinically causing shoulder droop and weak arm abduction.<br><br>Careful nerve identification reduces postoperative disability.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and marginal mandibular nerve (option C) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old alcoholic patient presents with severe trismus, toxic appearance, unilateral neck swelling, and medial tonsillar bulging. CT reveals multiloculated parapharyngeal abscess encasing carotid sheath. Which management strategy is most appropriate?",o:["Oral antibiotics alone","Immediate surgical drainage with intravenous antibiotics","Observation for spontaneous rupture","Outpatient needle aspiration only","Radiation therapy"],a:1,e:"Large multiloculated parapharyngeal abscesses near carotid sheath carry high risk of septic thrombosis and airway compromise. Severe trismus and dysphagia develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Prompt drainage combined with broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics is essential.<br><br>Oral antibiotics (option A), observation (option C), outpatient aspiration (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inadequate.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina initially improves after drainage but later redevelops fever and chest pain. Repeat imaging shows mediastinal abscesses. The infection most likely spread through the:",o:["Superficial cervical fascia","Thyrohyoid membrane","Subcutaneous tissue only","Parotid fascia","Danger space"],a:4,e:"The danger space extends from skull base into posterior mediastinum, permitting rapid descending spread of deep neck infections. Severe sepsis and chest pain develop clinically in mediastinitis.<br><br>Recognition of this pathway is important in persistent or recurrent infections after drainage.<br><br>Superficial fascia (option A), subcutaneous tissue (option C), parotid fascia (option D), and thyrohyoid membrane (option B) are less relevant routes.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old patient presents with slowly enlarging painless parapharyngeal mass causing medial displacement of the tonsil. The commonest benign tumor of parapharyngeal space is:",o:["Schwannoma","Pleomorphic adenoma","Lipoma","Lymphoma","Carotid body tumor"],a:1,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma commonly arises from deep lobe of parotid extending into parapharyngeal space. Dysphagia and medial tonsillar bulging develop clinically in larger lesions.<br><br>The tumor usually grows slowly and remains painless initially.<br><br>Schwannoma (option A), lipoma (option C), lymphoma (option D), and carotid body tumor (option E) are less common benign tumors.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A carotid body tumor characteristically presents as:",o:["Midline cystic swelling","Diffuse cellulitis","Posterior triangle abscess","Painful submental swelling","Pulsatile lateral neck mass movable sideways only"],a:4,e:"Carotid body tumors arise at carotid bifurcation and classically move horizontally but not vertically. Pulsatile neck swelling develops clinically in middle-aged adults.<br><br>These highly vascular tumors originate from paraganglionic tissue.<br><br>Midline cystic swelling (option A), posterior triangle abscess (option C), submental swelling (option D), and cellulitis (option B) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for evaluating vascularity of carotid body tumor is:",o:["Tympanometry","FNAC only","CT angiography","Audiometry","Sialography"],a:2,e:"CT angiography demonstrates vascular anatomy and carotid vessel involvement accurately. Bruit and pulsatile swelling develop clinically in carotid body tumors.<br><br>Preoperative vascular mapping assists surgical planning significantly.<br><br>Tympanometry (option A), FNAC alone (option B), audiometry (option D), and sialography (option E) are inadequate investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A vagal schwannoma in parapharyngeal space most commonly presents with:",o:["Tongue ulceration","Pulsatile tinnitus","Conductive deafness","Epistaxis","Hoarseness"],a:4,e:"Vagal schwannomas may compress or involve vagus nerve causing vocal cord dysfunction. Hoarseness develops clinically because recurrent laryngeal fibers become affected.<br><br>The mass is usually slow growing and painless.<br><br>Tongue ulceration (option A), pulsatile tinnitus (option B), epistaxis (option D), and conductive deafness (option C) are less typical findings.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carotid body tumor develops bradycardia during surgical manipulation because of stimulation of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Accessory nerve","Glossopharyngeal-carotid sinus reflex"],a:4,e:"Carotid sinus manipulation may trigger reflex bradycardia and hypotension during surgery. Dizziness and syncopal symptoms develop clinically in some patients preoperatively.<br><br>Careful anesthetic monitoring is therefore essential during excision.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), accessory nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option B) are less involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A highly vascular parapharyngeal tumor should not undergo routine FNAC because of risk of:",o:["Hearing loss","Massive hemorrhage","Facial paralysis","Air embolism","Trismus only"],a:1,e:"Vascular tumors such as paragangliomas carry significant bleeding risk during invasive procedures. Pulsatile swelling develops clinically in carotid body tumors.<br><br>Radiological vascular assessment is preferred before biopsy attempts.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A), facial paralysis (option C), air embolism (option D), and isolated trismus (option E) are less relevant risks.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal mass demonstrates widening of carotid bifurcation on imaging. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Vagal schwannoma","Carotid body tumor","Lipoma","Thyroglossal cyst"],a:2,e:"Carotid body tumors classically splay internal and external carotid arteries producing \"lyre sign.\" Pulsatile lateral neck swelling develops clinically.<br><br>Imaging findings are highly characteristic of paraganglioma.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), vagal schwannoma (option B), lipoma (option D), and thyroglossal cyst (option E) lack this sign.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest malignant tumor presenting as posterior triangle neck mass in adults is:",o:["Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma","Hemangioma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:2,e:"Cervical nodal metastasis from upper aerodigestive tract cancers commonly presents as lateral neck mass. Weight loss and dysphagia develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Adult neck masses should be considered malignant until proven otherwise.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), branchial cyst (option B), hemangioma (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are less concerning.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with vagal schwannoma undergoes surgery and develops postoperative vocal cord paralysis. The injured structure is the:",o:["Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:4,e:"Vagal schwannomas arise from vagus nerve sheath and nerve sacrifice may be unavoidable surgically. Hoarseness develops clinically after unilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Preoperative counseling regarding voice outcomes is important.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option C) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic lateral neck mass in an adult smoker should be considered:",o:["Congenital branchial cyst until proven otherwise","Thyroglossal cyst primarily","Dermoid cyst primarily","Lipoma primarily","Metastatic cystic nodal disease until proven otherwise"],a:4,e:"Cystic nodal metastases from HPV-related oropharyngeal carcinoma may mimic branchial cysts. Dysphagia and occult tonsillar lesions develop clinically in adults.<br><br>Careful endoscopic examination and biopsy are mandatory.<br><br>Congenital branchial cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option C), lipoma (option D), and thyroglossal cyst (option B) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sympathetic chain schwannoma most characteristically develops postoperative:",o:["Facial paralysis","Horner syndrome","Conductive deafness","Bell palsy","Trismus"],a:1,e:"Sympathetic chain injury may produce ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis after tumor excision. Neck swelling develops clinically before surgery because of slow-growing schwannoma.<br><br>This complication should be discussed preoperatively.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), conductive deafness (option C), Bell palsy (option D), and trismus (option E) are unrelated outcomes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with posterior triangle transilluminant swelling increasing during crying most likely has:",o:["Lymphoma","Carotid body tumor","Cystic hygroma","Metastatic node","Schwannoma"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma is a congenital lymphatic malformation commonly involving posterior triangle. Progressive enlargement develops clinically during crying or infection.<br><br>Brilliant transillumination is a useful examination finding.<br><br>Lymphoma (option A), carotid body tumor (option B), metastatic node (option D), and schwannoma (option E) do not transilluminate similarly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic cervical node from occult primary requires which investigation for identifying hidden mucosal tumor?",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Vestibular testing","Tympanometry","Sialography","Panendoscopy with directed biopsies"],a:4,e:"Occult upper aerodigestive tract primaries frequently present with metastatic neck nodes. Dysphagia and weight loss may develop clinically later.<br><br>Panendoscopy allows systematic evaluation of nasopharynx, oropharynx, hypopharynx, and larynx.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), tympanometry (option C), sialography (option D), and vestibular testing (option B) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carotid body tumor demonstrates cranial nerve palsies preoperatively. This usually indicates:",o:["Benign localized disease only","Large advanced tumor","Thyroid metastasis","Middle ear involvement","Salivary gland infection"],a:1,e:"Advanced carotid body tumors may compress adjacent lower cranial nerves. Dysphagia and hoarseness develop clinically because of neural involvement.<br><br>Larger Shamblin grade tumors carry greater operative morbidity.<br><br>Localized disease (option A), thyroid metastasis (option C), middle ear involvement (option D), and salivary infection (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless rubbery posterior triangle mass associated with fever and night sweats most likely suggests:",o:["Lipoma","Reactive lymphadenitis","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst","Lymphoma"],a:4,e:"Lymphoma commonly presents with painless rubbery cervical lymphadenopathy. Fever, weight loss, and night sweats develop clinically as \"B symptoms.\"<br><br>Posterior triangle involvement is frequent in Hodgkin lymphoma.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), reactive lymphadenitis (option B), branchial cyst (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option C) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep lobe parotid tumor extending into parapharyngeal space commonly presents with:",o:["Medial tonsillar bulge","Conductive hearing loss","Facial cellulitis","Torticollis","Nasal septal perforation"],a:0,e:"Deep lobe parotid tumors extend medially into parapharyngeal space causing tonsillar displacement. Dysphagia develops clinically with enlarging masses.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma remains the commonest pathology.<br><br>Conductive hearing loss (option B), cellulitis (option C), torticollis (option D), and septal perforation (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck mass undergoes FNAC revealing keratinizing squamous cells. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Lipoma","Neurofibroma","Schwannoma","Hemangioma","Metastatic squamous carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Keratinizing squamous cells in cervical node aspirate strongly suggest metastatic squamous malignancy. Dysphagia and smoking history develop clinically in many patients.<br><br>Primary tumors commonly arise in upper aerodigestive tract mucosa.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), schwannoma (option C), hemangioma (option D), and neurofibroma (option B) lack such cytology.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important complication during excision of carotid body tumor is injury to the:",o:["Lower cranial nerves and carotid vessels","Tympanic membrane","Facial artery only","Thyroid cartilage","Eustachian tube"],a:0,e:"Carotid body tumors are highly vascular and intimately related to neurovascular structures. Massive hemorrhage and cranial neuropathies develop clinically after injury.<br><br>Preoperative imaging and meticulous dissection are essential.<br><br>Tympanic membrane (option B), facial artery alone (option C), thyroid cartilage (option D), and Eustachian tube (option E) are less important concerns.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cystic hygroma causing airway compromise in infancy is best initially managed with:",o:["Observation only","Radiotherapy","Chemotherapy","Thyroidectomy","Airway stabilization"],a:4,e:"Large cervical hygromas may compress airway significantly in infants. Respiratory distress develops clinically because of extensive soft tissue involvement.<br><br>Airway management takes priority before definitive surgery or sclerotherapy.<br><br>Observation (option A), chemotherapy (option C), thyroidectomy (option D), and radiotherapy (option B) are inappropriate emergencies.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with malignant cervical node and unknown primary has PET-CT arranged primarily to:",o:["Assess hearing function","Identify occult primary tumor and distant metastasis","Diagnose Ménière disease","Evaluate facial paralysis","Detect otitis media"],a:1,e:"PET-CT is valuable in detecting metabolically active occult head and neck primaries. Weight loss and persistent cervical lymphadenopathy develop clinically in metastatic disease.<br><br>It also assists staging by identifying distant metastatic spread.<br><br>Hearing assessment (option A), Ménière diagnosis (option C), facial paralysis evaluation (option D), and otitis detection (option E) are unrelated purposes.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with schwannoma of cervical sympathetic chain develops postoperative ptosis and anhidrosis. This complication is:",o:["Frey syndrome","Sjögren syndrome","Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Eagle syndrome","Horner syndrome"],a:4,e:"Sympathetic chain injury causes ipsilateral ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis. Slow-growing lateral neck swelling develops clinically before surgery in sympathetic schwannomas.<br><br>Patients should be warned regarding this predictable complication preoperatively.<br><br>Frey syndrome (option A), Ramsay Hunt syndrome (option C), Eagle syndrome (option D), and Sjögren syndrome (option B) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A hard fixed supraclavicular lymph node in an elderly smoker most strongly suggests:",o:["Benign reactive hyperplasia","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial anomaly","Metastatic malignancy"],a:4,e:"Hard fixed supraclavicular nodes are highly suspicious for metastatic cancer. Weight loss and dysphagia develop clinically in many patients.<br><br>Thoracic and upper gastrointestinal malignancies commonly metastasize to this region.<br><br>Reactive hyperplasia (option A), sebaceous cyst (option C), branchial anomaly (option D), and cystic hygroma (option B) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carotid body tumor is planned for surgery. Preoperative embolization is sometimes performed mainly to:",o:["Improve hearing","Reduce salivation","Prevent trismus","Enhance thyroid function","Reduce intraoperative blood loss"],a:4,e:"Carotid body tumors are highly vascular lesions with significant bleeding risk during excision. Pulsatile neck swelling develops clinically before diagnosis.<br><br>Preoperative embolization may facilitate safer surgical dissection in selected large tumors.<br><br>Hearing improvement (option A), trismus prevention (option C), thyroid enhancement (option D), and salivation reduction (option B) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy from nasopharyngeal carcinoma most commonly presents with nodes in:",o:["Submental region","Posterior triangle and upper deep cervical chain","Preauricular region only","Occipital region only","Submandibular triangle exclusively"],a:1,e:"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma commonly metastasizes early to upper deep cervical nodes. Nasal obstruction and hearing symptoms develop clinically in many patients.<br><br>Posterior triangle involvement is especially frequent.<br><br>Submental region (option A), preauricular region (option C), occipital nodes (option D), and isolated submandibular nodes (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with large cervical metastatic node develops overlying skin fixation and ulceration. This finding suggests:",o:["Benign inflammatory disease","Congenital lesion","Simple reactive hyperplasia","Tuberculous abscess only","Advanced extracapsular spread"],a:4,e:"Skin fixation and ulceration indicate advanced nodal disease with extracapsular extension. Pain and weight loss develop clinically in advanced metastatic malignancy.<br><br>These findings worsen prognosis significantly.<br><br>Benign inflammation (option A), reactive hyperplasia (option C), tuberculous abscess only (option D), and congenital lesions (option B) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parapharyngeal schwannoma demonstrates smooth displacement of carotid vessels on imaging without vessel splaying. The tumor most likely arises from the:",o:["Carotid body","Deep cervical fascia","Branchial cleft","Thyroglossal tract","Vagus nerve"],a:4,e:"Vagal schwannomas displace carotid vessels together, unlike carotid body tumors that splay them apart. Hoarseness develops clinically because of vagal involvement.<br><br>MRI characteristics help distinguish these tumors preoperatively.<br><br>Carotid body origin (option A), branchial cleft (option C), thyroglossal tract (option D), and fascia (option B) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with posterior triangle neck mass has biopsy showing Reed-Sternberg cells. The diagnosis is:",o:["Metastatic squamous carcinoma","Hodgkin lymphoma","Schwannoma","Carotid body tumor","Liposarcoma"],a:1,e:"Reed-Sternberg cells are characteristic of Hodgkin lymphoma. Painless cervical lymphadenopathy develops clinically with constitutional \"B symptoms.\"<br><br>Posterior triangle nodes are commonly involved in early disease.<br><br>Metastatic carcinoma (option A), schwannoma (option C), carotid body tumor (option D), and liposarcoma (option E) lack these cells.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cervical metastasis from occult primary undergoes panendoscopy. The procedure includes examination of:",o:["Nasopharynx, oropharynx, hypopharynx, and larynx","Middle ear and mastoid only","Orbit and cranial cavity only","Esophagus only","Thyroid gland only"],a:0,e:"Panendoscopy systematically evaluates mucosal surfaces of upper aerodigestive tract. Dysphagia and cervical nodal metastasis develop clinically in occult primary tumors.<br><br>Directed biopsies help identify hidden malignancies.<br><br>Middle ear (option B), orbit (option C), isolated esophagus (option D), and thyroid only (option E) are insufficient evaluations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with giant carotid body tumor develops severe intraoperative hemorrhage. The tumor derives embryologically from:",o:["Neural crest paraganglionic tissue","Branchial cleft epithelium","Thyroid follicular cells","Mesodermal cartilage","Salivary duct tissue"],a:0,e:"Carotid body tumors arise from neural crest-derived paraganglionic chemoreceptor tissue. Pulsatile vascular neck swelling develops clinically with slow enlargement.<br><br>Their rich vascularity explains operative bleeding risks.<br><br>Branchial epithelium (option B), thyroid cells (option C), cartilage (option D), and salivary tissue (option E) are unrelated origins.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cervical nodal metastasis from unknown primary remains occult after imaging and endoscopy. The next management commonly includes:",o:["Blind radical mastoidectomy","Directed biopsies with possible tonsillectomy","Observation only","Cochlear implantation","Septoplasty"],a:1,e:"Occult oropharyngeal primaries may remain hidden within tonsillar crypts despite imaging. Persistent metastatic cervical nodes develop clinically in these patients.<br><br>Tonsillectomy and directed biopsies improve primary tumor detection rates.<br><br>Mastoidectomy (option A), observation (option C), cochlear implantation (option D), and septoplasty (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 46-year-old patient presents with a slowly enlarging parapharyngeal mass causing dysphagia and obstructive sleep symptoms. MRI demonstrates a highly vascular lesion splaying the internal and external carotid arteries, while urinary catecholamines are mildly elevated. Which additional tumor association should specifically be screened for in this patient?",o:["Medullary thyroid carcinoma and pheochromocytoma","Nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","Pleomorphic adenoma of parotid","Papillary thyroid carcinoma","Warthin tumor"],a:0,e:"Carotid body tumors are paragangliomas and may occur in familial syndromes associated with pheochromocytoma and medullary thyroid carcinoma. Pulsatile neck swelling develops clinically with lower cranial neuropathies in advanced lesions.<br><br>Biochemical screening is important before surgery because catecholamine-secreting tumors may precipitate hypertensive crises intraoperatively.<br><br>Angiofibroma (option B), pleomorphic adenoma (option C), papillary carcinoma (option D), and Warthin tumor (option E) lack this association.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoes excision of large vagal schwannoma extending from skull base to carotid bifurcation. Postoperatively he develops hoarseness, aspiration, uvular deviation, and ipsilateral vocal cord paralysis. The combined findings are most consistent with injury to:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve alone","Glossopharyngeal nerve only","Vagus nerve proximal to pharyngeal branches","Cervical sympathetic chain","Recurrent laryngeal nerve only"],a:2,e:"High vagal injury affects pharyngeal plexus and recurrent laryngeal components simultaneously. Aspiration and palatal weakness develop clinically along with vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Tumors extending toward skull base increase risk of complex lower cranial neuropathies during excision.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve alone (option B), sympathetic chain (option D), and isolated recurrent laryngeal nerve injury (option E) do not explain all findings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old smoker presents with cystic level II cervical node. PET-CT fails to identify a primary lesion. Bilateral tonsillectomy reveals a 4 mm occult HPV-related carcinoma in tonsillar crypts. The most important reason for bilateral rather than unilateral tonsillectomy is:",o:["Prevention of postoperative bleeding","To improve swallowing postoperatively","Tonsils are highly vascular","Contralateral tonsils always contain dysplasia","HPV-associated tumors may be clinically occult and bilateral"],a:4,e:"HPV-related oropharyngeal carcinoma frequently presents with cystic cervical metastasis despite clinically normal tonsils. Tiny cryptic primaries develop clinically with minimal mucosal abnormality.<br><br>Bilateral tonsillectomy increases occult primary detection rates substantially in metastatic neck disease.<br><br>Bleeding prevention (option A), vascularity alone (option C), universal dysplasia (option D), and swallowing improvement (option B) are incorrect explanations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Shamblin III carotid body tumor develops massive intraoperative hemorrhage requiring carotid artery sacrifice. Which neurological complication is most feared immediately postoperatively?",o:["Facial nerve palsy","Horner syndrome","Ischemic stroke","Conductive hearing loss","Bell palsy"],a:2,e:"Large Shamblin III tumors encase carotid vessels extensively and may necessitate vascular sacrifice during resection. Hemiplegia and neurological deficits develop clinically after cerebral ischemia.<br><br>Preoperative balloon occlusion testing may help predict tolerance to carotid sacrifice.<br><br>Facial palsy (option A), Horner syndrome (option B), conductive hearing loss (option D), and Bell palsy (option E) are less catastrophic complications.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy from occult primary undergoes neck dissection. Histopathology demonstrates extracapsular nodal extension. This finding most strongly predicts:",o:["Reduced recurrence risk","Excellent prognosis with surgery alone","Low likelihood of distant metastasis","Benign reactive pathology","Increased locoregional recurrence and poorer survival"],a:4,e:"Extracapsular spread indicates aggressive metastatic disease with extension beyond nodal capsule. Local recurrence and distant metastases develop clinically more frequently in affected patients.<br><br>Adjuvant chemoradiotherapy is commonly indicated after surgery in such cases.<br><br>Reduced recurrence (option A), excellent prognosis (option B), benign pathology (option D), and low metastatic risk (option C) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sympathetic chain schwannoma develops postoperative ipsilateral ptosis, miosis, facial anhidrosis, and apparent enophthalmos. The pathophysiological basis of this syndrome is interruption of:",o:["Parasympathetic fibers from glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagal parasympathetic fibers","Facial nerve motor supply","Trigeminal sensory innervation","Preganglionic sympathetic fibers to superior cervical ganglion"],a:4,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain injury disrupts sympathetic supply to eye and facial sweat glands. Horner syndrome develops clinically after surgery for deep neck neurogenic tumors.<br><br>The sympathetic pathway ascends through cervical chain toward superior cervical ganglion.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal fibers (option A), facial motor supply (option C), trigeminal sensation (option D), and vagal fibers (option B) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep lobe parotid pleomorphic adenoma extending into parapharyngeal space undergoes transcervical-transparotid excision. Which postoperative complication most strongly suggests facial nerve trunk injury?",o:["Tongue deviation","Shoulder droop","Inability to close eye and mouth deviation","Horner syndrome","Severe dysphagia only"],a:2,e:"The facial nerve traverses parotid gland and may be injured during deep lobe tumor surgery. Facial asymmetry develops clinically with inability to close eyelids and oral incompetence.<br><br>Meticulous nerve identification is crucial during transparotid dissection.<br><br>Tongue deviation (option A), shoulder droop (option B), Horner syndrome (option D), and isolated dysphagia (option E) indicate different nerve injuries.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old patient presents with rapidly enlarging painful cervical mass fixed to surrounding structures, associated with weight loss and multiple cranial neuropathies. Biopsy demonstrates metastatic squamous carcinoma, but panendoscopy and PET-CT remain negative. The condition is best classified as:",o:["Primary branchial carcinoma","Carcinoma of unknown primary","Benign cervical lymphadenopathy","Lymphangioma","Neurofibromatosis"],a:1,e:"Metastatic cervical squamous carcinoma without detectable mucosal origin is termed carcinoma of unknown primary. Progressive nodal fixation and cranial neuropathies develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Management often includes comprehensive neck treatment with mucosal irradiation or surgery.<br><br>Primary branchial carcinoma (option A) is extremely controversial and rare, while lymphangioma (option D) and neurofibromatosis (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A highly vascular parapharyngeal tumor demonstrates \"salt and pepper\" appearance on MRI. The imaging pattern is most characteristic of:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Schwannoma","Paraganglioma","Liposarcoma","Reactive lymphadenopathy"],a:2,e:"Paragangliomas show characteristic MRI \"salt and pepper\" appearance due to flow voids and hypervascularity. Pulsatile neck swelling develops clinically in carotid body tumors.<br><br>This imaging pattern strongly supports diagnosis of highly vascular neuroendocrine tumors.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), schwannoma (option B), liposarcoma (option D), and reactive nodes (option E) lack this appearance.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic supraclavicular lymphadenopathy from occult thoracic malignancy develops chylous fistula after radical neck dissection. The injured structure is most likely the:",o:["External jugular vein","Internal carotid artery","Thoracic duct","Cervical sympathetic chain","Vagus nerve"],a:2,e:"Thoracic duct enters venous system near left supraclavicular region and may be injured during lower neck dissections. Persistent milky drainage develops clinically after surgery.<br><br>Large chyle leaks may cause electrolyte imbalance, malnutrition, and delayed wound healing.<br><br>External jugular vein (option A), carotid artery (option B), sympathetic chain (option D), and vagus nerve (option E) do not produce chylous fistula.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
];